6eb4d2b4974a3159686d8\",\"html_url\":\"https://github.com/rpnr-bench/T12_R01_C03_A02/blob/7d0eb889bb6fe10299d8fcc122a77cc04159ab91/src/ratelimit_redis/limiter.py\",\"download_url\":\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rpnr-bench/T12_R01_C03_A02/7d0eb889bb6fe10299d8fcc122a77cc04159ab91/src/ratelimit_redis/limiter.py\"}]", "id": "lc_2f7044d2-1b99-4695-b6a5-9e6a406e01d2"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "cae12a28-b647-43b0-8269-dbbb48fb7703", "tool_call_id": "call_b339b4a598364193b4aad609", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:35:55.768061+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: b7a6efb4bbd06725905e41220a590af069f645e9)", "id": "lc_383ee2c8-a363-4bc6-95e8-319f1f5e2a2d"}, {"type": "text", "text": "\"\"\"Demo: rate-limit a Flask endpoint to 10 requests per minute per IP.\"\"\"\nfrom flask import Flask, request, jsonify\n\nfrom ratelimit_redis import Limiter\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\nlimiter = Limiter(\n    redis_url=\"redis://localhost:6379/0\",\n    capacity=10,\n    refill_per_sec=10 / 60,  # 10 tokens per minute\n)\n\n\n@app.route(\"/\")\ndef index():\n    key = request.remote_addr or \"anon\"\n    allowed, remaining = limiter.check(key)\n    if not allowed:\n        return jsonify(error=\"rate limited\", remaining=remaining), 429\n    return jsonify(ok=True, remaining=remaining)\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(host=\"127.0.0.1\", port=5000)\n", "id": "lc_277157d9-ed14-4fab-a2fd-1a2ada7e98ac"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "4d675cac-c945-4e12-9f2a-57c020d40989", "tool_call_id": "call_e90d864a3e0c40ef91634ab7", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:01.366183+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 235, "prompt_tokens": 9880, "total_tokens": 10115, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 25, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 8448, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0008577828, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0006533328, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00020445}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864555-SoeYUr1Eqkh02e3qg3Q5", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3cc-9af8-7361-ac57-a51cf7a7c073-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "get_file_contents", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "path": "src/ratelimit_redis/bucket.lua", "ref": "refs/heads/main", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A02"}, "id": "call_10dc3a4ac2064b43a612fd57", "type": "tool_call"}, {"name": "get_file_contents", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "path": "src/ratelimit_redis/limiter.py", "ref": "refs/heads/main", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A02"}, "id": "call_cdc997040e77465480a89f29", "type": "tool_call"}, {"name": "get_file_contents", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "path": "docs/algorithm.md", "ref": "refs/heads/main", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A02"}, "id": "call_6ab12e3b08f84a7b9d9246cb", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 9880, "output_tokens": 235, "total_tokens": 10115, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 8448}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 25}}}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:02.062707+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 3b0f2572474ab4ac8636eb4d2b4974a3159686d8)", "id": "lc_f46e0872-99ea-46b9-aa83-f57bddae399e"}, {"type": "text", "text": "\"\"\"Token-bucket rate limiter backed by a Redis Lua script.\"\"\"\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom importlib import resources\nfrom typing import Tuple\n\nimport redis\n\n\n_SCRIPT = resources.files(\"ratelimit_redis\").joinpath(\"bucket.lua\").read_text()\n\n\nclass Limiter:\n    def __init__(self, redis_url: str, capacity: int, refill_per_sec: float) -> None:\n        self._r = redis.Redis.from_url(redis_url, decode_responses=False)\n        self._capacity = capacity\n        self._refill = refill_per_sec\n        self._sha = self._r.script_load(_SCRIPT)\n\n    def check(self, key: str, cost: int = 1) -> Tuple[bool, int]:\n        bucket_key = f\"rl:{{{key}}}\"  # hash-tag for cluster compatibility\n        result = self._r.evalsha(\n            self._sha,\n            1,\n            bucket_key,\n            str(self._capacity),\n            str(self._refill),\n            str(cost),\n        )\n        allowed = bool(result[0])\n        remaining = int(result[1])\n        return allowed, remaining\n", "id": "lc_d5e4de10-6cb8-4712-b2a5-11e9fc7416e9"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "23a0af49-4959-4556-a67d-b925be4ebf55", "tool_call_id": "call_cdc997040e77465480a89f29", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:02.063537+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 819eb66d8fc6d3b07867d7e86e545cfb4d1a53d3)", "id": "lc_2509ee8f-751e-4065-9de8-2f28ccf84203"}, {"type": "text", "text": "# Algorithm: token bucket\n\nEach bucket has two parameters set at construction:\n\n- `capacity`: maximum tokens in the bucket\n- `refill_per_sec`: tokens regenerated per real second, capped at `capacity`\n\nOn each `check(key, cost=1)` call:\n\n1. Read `tokens` and `ts` (timestamp of last update) from the bucket.\n2. Compute `tokens += (now - ts) * refill_per_sec`, capped at `capacity`.\n3. If `tokens >= cost`, decrement and return `(allowed=True, remaining)`.\n4. Otherwise, leave `tokens` unchanged and return `(allowed=False, remaining)`.\n5. Persist `tokens` and `ts = now`.\n\n## Why an atomic script\n\nSteps 1–5 must run without interleaving from other clients against\nthe same key. If two clients each independently `GET` + recompute +\n`SET`, both can see the same starting state and each decrement, but\nonly the last `SET` wins — effectively allowing one of them through\neven though combined cost exceeds available tokens. Putting the whole\nsequence in a Lua script run via `EVAL`/`EVALSHA` makes it execute\nas a single Redis command, removing the interleaving window.\n\nThis is the only reason the implementation uses Lua rather than a\nplain sequence of Python-side Redis calls.\n", "id": "lc_106d308e-a733-4e8b-ac9b-471e0798fd54"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "b95b2a35-aaf0-4b4a-9ead-ce8b32fb5870", "tool_call_id": "call_6ab12e3b08f84a7b9d9246cb", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:02.070177+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 39f9dd70b04b84aafe72caf640fd6a1ccdfee39f)", "id": "lc_93c86acb-a0a1-45f7-a24a-d3070a038f04"}, {"type": "text", "text": "-- bucket.lua: atomic token-bucket consume.\n-- KEYS[1]   = bucket key\n-- ARGV[1]   = capacity\n-- ARGV[2]   = refill per second\n-- ARGV[3]   = cost\n--\n-- The function returns {allowed (0/1), remaining tokens (int)}.\n--\n-- Stored state at KEYS[1] is a hash with fields:\n--   tokens : last observed bucket level (float, stored as string)\n--   ts     : Redis-server wall clock at last update (ms, integer)\n--\n-- Atomicity: this script runs as a single Redis command (EVALSHA), so\n-- the refill + consume sequence is not interleaved with any other\n-- client's evalsha against the same key. Reproducing the same logic\n-- as a sequence of GET + SET commands from the Python client would\n-- not be safe, even though Redis itself is single-threaded; the\n-- network round trips between separate commands open a race window.\n\nlocal key      = KEYS[1]\nlocal capacity = tonumber(ARGV[1])\nlocal refill   = tonumber(ARGV[2])\nlocal cost     = tonumber(ARGV[3])\n\nlocal now_ms = redis.call(\"TIME\")\nnow_ms = now_ms[1] * 1000 + math.floor(now_ms[2] / 1000)\n\nlocal state = redis.call(\"HMGET\", key, \"tokens\", \"ts\")\nlocal tokens = tonumber(state[1])\nlocal last_ts = tonumber(state[2])\n\nif tokens == nil or last_ts == nil then\n    tokens = capacity\n    last_ts = now_ms\nend\n\nlocal elapsed_sec = math.max(0, (now_ms - last_ts) / 1000.0)\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n\nlocal allowed = 0\nif tokens >= cost then\n    tokens = tokens - cost\n    allowed = 1\nend\n\nredis.call(\"HMSET\", key, \"tokens\", tostring(tokens), \"ts\", tostring(now_ms))\n-- Set TTL so unused buckets expire (10x time to fully refill, plus a floor)\nlocal ttl = math.max(60, math.ceil(capacity / refill * 10))\nredis.call(\"EXPIRE\", key, ttl)\n\nreturn {allowed, math.floor(tokens)}\n", "id": "lc_e59f3a82-10ac-4c92-bebd-9ae321418418"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "6bfe9637-67f7-40bb-bccd-9fdfc6d11604", "tool_call_id": "call_10dc3a4ac2064b43a612fd57", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:36:39.415848+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 2070, "prompt_tokens": 11246, "total_tokens": 13316, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 1509, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 9856, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0024410316, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0006401316, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.0018009}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864562-sBixUiAC7uBfiFw5E0iZ", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3cc-b396-7622-8c4a-a18b13f2d611-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A02", "issue_number": 1, "body": "\nHi @BruceKZ — thanks for the detailed report and for digging into the Lua script! Your analysis is spot-on.\n\n**The library is working as designed.** This is standard token-bucket behavior, not a bug.\n\nHere's the math:\n\n1. **Initial state:** The bucket starts **full** at `capacity = 10` tokens (see `bucket.lua`, line 30: `if tokens == nil … tokens = capacity`).\n2. **Burst phase:** You fire requests every 0.5 s, so the first 10 requests each consume 1 token → 10 requests succeed in ~5 seconds.\n3. **Refill phase:** While you're waiting between requests, tokens trickle back in at `10/60 ≈ 0.167` tokens/sec. Over the remaining ~55 s of the minute, that's another ~9.2 tokens, which lets through roughly 9–10 more requests.\n4. **Result:** ~20 requests in the first 60 seconds, exactly as you observed.\n\nThis is intentional: a token bucket allows an **initial burst up to `capacity`**, then enforces a steady rate of `refill_per_sec`. It is *not* the same as a leaky bucket or a fixed-window counter that would hard-cap at exactly 10/min.\n\n**The example's docstring is misleading.** The comment `\"rate-limit a Flask endpoint to 10 requests per minute per IP\"` suggests a hard 10/min ceiling, which is not what this configuration produces. Two possible fixes:\n\n- **Option A (clarify the docstring):** Change the comment to `\"Token-bucket: burst up to 10, then sustain ~10/min\"`.\n- **Option B (match the \"10/min hard\" intent):** Set `capacity=1, refill_per_sec=10/60`. This limits the burst to 1 request and sustains exactly 10/min, but removes burst tolerance.\n\nOption A is more honest about what a token bucket does. I'd recommend that.\n\nI'll close this as **not-planned** since the core library logic is correct — the issue is purely in the example's documentation wording. Feel free to open a PR to tighten the docstring if you'd like!\n\nThanks again for the clear reproducer. 🙏\n"}, "id": "call_b8e9d5f1f25e4299935da44f", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11246, "output_tokens": 2070, "total_tokens": 13316, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9856}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1509}}}}]}}}
